<subSubSection id="C32DF8BD9659FFF1FF2716693AB0FDAD" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="1786" pageId="0" pageNumber="1785" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B88AB369659FFF1FF2716693813FE6C" blockId="0.[178,1085,1545,1597]" lastBlockId="1.[178,1086,219,387]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="1786" pageId="0" pageNumber="1785">
Description: Length: 
<quantity id="4CCF06D39659FFF0FE7816693B44F9F0" box="[493,587,1545,1567]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3599999999999999" pageId="0" pageNumber="1785" unit="mm" value="13.6">13.6 mm</quantity>
; length of fore-body: 
<quantity id="4CCF06D39659FFF0FCB816693A71F9F0" box="[813,894,1545,1567]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1785" unit="mm" value="7.5">7.5 mm</quantity>
. Body deep black, glossy; femora and tibiae black, palpi, antennae and tarsi dark brown. Fore-body: 
<figureCitation id="130CB7B39659FFF0FC6E16473D37F9D3" box="[1019,1080,1575,1597]" captionStart="Figs 1-2" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1342,1364]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,224,1281]" captionTargetId="figure-83@10.[178,1085,212,1308]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 1-2: Fore-body (fb), aedoeagus in lateral view (al), aedoeagus in ventral view (av), male sternite VII (s7), male sternite VIII (s8) of: 1: P. magna; 2: P. ullrichi Fig. 1: P. magna 1fb 1al 1av 1s7 1s8" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5873558" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5873558/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="1785">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
. Head transverse (1.6 x 
<quantity id="4CCF06D39658FFF1FE0B10BB38D3FF1F" box="[414,476,219,240]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
), bearing a large foveate puncture near anterior margin near bases of antennae, a puncture on inner margin of eye anteriorly and two more posteriorly, half a dozen punctures near posterro-lateral angles, a single row of closely set punctures along posterior margin, the disc impunctate. Pronotum slightly elongate (2.1 x 
<quantity id="4CCF06D39658FFF1FC6711533D3CFEA7" box="[1010,1075,307,328]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
), with discal series of 6-7 small punctures and strongly arcuate lateral series of 3-4 punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B88AB369658FFF1FF2711F23B2AFE0C" blockId="1.[178,1085,402,483]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786">
Elytra elongate (2.3 x 
<quantity id="4CCF06D39658FFF1FE3D11F338E4FE47" box="[424,491,403,424]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
), the disc of each elytron with 5 longitudinal series of numerous rather small punctures. Abdomen fairly coarsely and densely punctured, the interstices devoid of microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B88AB369658FFF1FF2711923AB0FDAD" blockId="1.[178,1085,498,579]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786">
Male: posterior margin sternite VII with a small shallow median emargination, laterally with a single marginal row of ca.15 stout black bristles; sternite VIII with a deep narrow emargination extending 3/8 
<superScript id="7C42067E9658FFF1FE5D124638D4FDDB" attach="left" box="[456,475,550,564]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786">ths</superScript>
the length of sternite; aedoeagus: 
<figureCitation id="130CB7B39658FFF1FCA3124D3A7DFDAC" box="[822,882,557,579]" captionStart="Figs 1-2" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1342,1364]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,224,1281]" captionTargetId="figure-83@10.[178,1085,212,1308]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 1-2: Fore-body (fb), aedoeagus in lateral view (al), aedoeagus in ventral view (av), male sternite VII (s7), male sternite VIII (s8) of: 1: P. magna; 2: P. ullrichi Fig. 1: P. magna 1fb 1al 1av 1s7 1s8" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5873558" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5873558/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786">Figs 1</figureCitation>
al, 1av.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32DF8BD9658FFF1FF2712323B82FD4D" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B88AB369658FFF1FF2712323B82FD4D" blockId="1.[178,1085,594,675]" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786">
This new species is the giant of the genus in our regions (there are comparably large ones in 
<collectingCountry id="F320EBA69658FFF1FF45120F3821FD6A" box="[208,302,623,645]" name="Australia" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786">Australia</collectingCountry>
) and as such easy to recognise. Its facies, sculpture and sexual characters show that it belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C37D0B59658FFF1FE5612ED3B4BFD4D" baseAuthorityName="CAMERON" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[451,580,653,674]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pseudolathra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigerrima">
<emphasis id="B94377249658FFF1FE5612ED3B4BFD4D" box="[451,580,653,674]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="1786">P. nigerrima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
